							I remember vividly the first time I encountered <i>The New Yorker</i> in my senior English class in a Denver public high school.  My teacher announced at the beginning of the year that we would each be given a copy of <i>The New Yorker</i> every Friday, which we would be allowed to peruse for half of the class and then weâ€™d write a short essay on one of the articles. Incredibly, the magazine was ours to keep, an unaccustomed boon for students in a woefully under-funded school district.  I donâ€™t think many of my classmatesâ€™ copies ever made it past the trashcans in the hallwayâ€”the consensus was that the magazine was boring, snooty, and irrelevant with almost no pictures apart from undecipherable cartoonsâ€”but I took my New Yorkers home and hoarded them under my bed.  Iâ€™d never seen anything like <i>The New Yorker</i>, full of literate, witty articles about a faraway worldâ€”the East Coastâ€”with a short story in every issue, a delight I hadnâ€™t encountered in any of the magazines my parents subscribed to. <br />
<br />
Despite choosing to live in the state where I grew up, ever since then Iâ€™ve maintained a steady New York literary media diet, subscribing to <i>The New Yorker</i>, <i>The New York Times Book Review</i>, <i>The New York Review of Books</i>, and the New York-based <i>Poets & Writers</i> over the years.  Whenever one of these publications includes a mention of Colorado or the West, I read the article eagerly, hoping to see my home accurately portrayed and the regionâ€™s authors fairly judged, but usually I am disappointed, as I was by <a target="_blank" href="http://www.newyorker.com/main/magazine/" title="Jonathan Franzenâ€™s essay, â€œMy Bird Problem,â€? in the August 8 & 15 <i>New Yorker</i>.">Jonathan Franzenâ€™s essay, â€œMy Bird Problem,â€? in the August 8 & 15 <i>New Yorker</i>.</a><br />
<br />
Franzenâ€™s essay isnâ€™t about Colorado per seâ€”it focuses on his growing concern about the environment and the dissolution of his first marriageâ€”but Iâ€™m a Coloradoan, so the brief mentions of my state are the most important part for me.  What local insight did I glean from the literary master?  Weâ€™ve disappointed him, it seems.  In 1990, Franzen separated from his wife and she moved to Colorado Springs. â€œBy fleeing to the land of open skies,â€? he writes, â€œmy wife hoped to restore her independent nature.â€?  He writes of her reading habits: â€œShe became fascinated with narratives of pioneer womenâ€”tough, oppressed, resourceful wives who buried dead infants, watched freak June blizzards kill their crops and livestock, and survived to write about it.â€?  <br />
<br />
Franzen visits Colorado, hoping to patch up the relationship, but is not impressed with what he sees, which doesnâ€™t match his childhood fantasies of the West: â€œEvery crest in the open road opened up new vistas of irrigation-intensive monoculture, mining-scarred hillsides, and parking lots full of nature loversâ€™ cars.â€?  But thereâ€™s moreâ€”when he and his wife examined eleven different places where they might move, including Boulder and Santa Fe, they found â€œthings to fault in each of them.â€?  Is this what the Rocky Mountain region has become to the rest of the countryâ€”a place for East Coast types to visit and find lacking when compared to the myths they carry around in their minds, and then use the disenchantment they experience as the fodder to generate a <i>New Yorker</i> essay?  I guess I shouldnâ€™t be too upset about the New York-centric views of the magazine; after all, itâ€™s called <i>The New Yorker</i>.  Still, itâ€™s unfortunate that all of the most powerful forces in Americaâ€™s literary culture share this East Coast outlook.<br />
<br />
Even more annoying than Coloradoâ€™s dismissal by Franzen, who is already hated by thousands as The Guy Who Ruined Oprahâ€™s Book Club For Everyone, is the review treatment that books of some Western writers receive by the <i>New York Times</i>, whose Sunday book section is, for better or worse, the book review of record.  Most often, the <i>Book Review</i> ignores Western writers altogetherâ€”but occasionally it pays them attention of the most condescending sort.  Nothing was worse in this respect than <a target="_blank" href="http://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9C07E7DA1F3CF930A15756C0A9629C8B63" title="Jonathan Miles' review">Jonathan Miles' review</a> of Kent Harufâ€™s <i>Eventide</i> (the follow-up to National Book Award-nominated <i>Plainsong</i>) which ran in the <i>Book Review</i> last May.  <br />
<br />
Miles began with this snide opening: â€œI can't support this with demographic particulars, but here goes: many of the same readers who were drawn to Kent Haruf's best-selling novel, <i>Plainsong</i>, are equally drawn to Pottery Barn furniture.â€?  The review grew more unfair from thereâ€”Miles quoted statements from the prose in a Pottery Barn catalogue that he claimed were applicable to Harufâ€™s work, and because he couldnâ€™t understand how a book set in rural Colorado could become nationally popular on its own merits, he offered this specious theory: â€œLike antique reproductions, 'alternativeâ€™ country music and the Slow Food movement, <i>Plainsong</i> was a life raft for people who felt they were drowning in the sour froth of pop cynicism.â€?  By â€œpeople,â€? he clearly meant â€œNew Yorkers,â€? because all the Coloradoans I know who read <i>Plainsong</i> found it to be a literary blessing of the simplest sort: A believable, moving representation of life in the state they call home. For the record, I loved <i>Eventide</i>, and said so in my review for the <a target="_blank" href="http://www.insidedenver.com/drmn/books/article/0,1299,DRMN_63_2863170,00.html" title="Rocky Mountain News">Rocky Mountain News</a>.<br />
<br />
The problem is, many, many more bookish people read <i>The New York Times Book Review</i> than read any of the book reviews that are generated in the West.  And the review problem further exacerbates the publication problemâ€”the publishing industry, based in New York, seems less likely to publish the work of Western writers than East Coast writers, in part because they must think Western books wonâ€™t sell as well.  And itâ€™s true, they wonâ€™t, if they arenâ€™t able to grab any attention from the East Coast media juggernaut that drives the sales of books.  <br />
<br />
Iâ€™m not canceling my subscription to <i>The New Yorker</i> or the <i>Book Review</i>, but I canâ€™t help but wish there were some way for Western literature to gain equal, fair representation in the national media.  Until that happens, meet me out on the range somewhereâ€”over the campfire, Iâ€™ll tell you which books are the good ones.
